05014nam a22006615i 9781478022909DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780229097 a10.1515/97814780229092doi  a(DE-B1597)624921  a(OCoLC)1312726664  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0240002bisacsh04a325/.30098223//eng/20211103eng  aMK 2700qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123040:1 aPratt, Mary Louise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlanetary Longings /cMary Louise Pratt. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (348 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDissident Acts : 1400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Sitting in the Light of the Great Solar TV -- tPart I. Future Tensions -- t1. Modernity’s False Promises -- t2. Why the Virgin of Zapopan Went to Los Angeles -- t3. Mobility and the Politics of Belonging, -- t4. Fire, Water, and Wandering Women -- t5. Planetarized Indigeneity -- t6. Anthropocene as Concept and Chronotope -- t7. Mutations of the Contact Zone: From Human to More-Than-Human -- t8. Is This Gitmo or Club Med? -- t9. Authoritarianism 2020: Lessons from Chile -- t10. The Ethnographer’s Arrival -- t11. Rigoberta Menchú and the Geopolitics of Truth -- t12. The Politics of Reenactment -- t13. Translation, Contagion, Infiltration -- t14. Thinking across the Colonial Divide -- t15. The Futurology of Independence -- t16. Remembering Anticolonialism -- tCoda: Airways, the Politics of Breath -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tPublication History0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Planetary Longings eminent cultural theorist Mary Louise Pratt posits that the last decade of the twentieth century and the first decades of the twenty-first mark a turning point in the human and planetary condition. Examining the forces of modernity, neoliberalism, coloniality, and indigeneity in their pre- and postmillennial forms, Pratt reflects on the crisis of futurity that accompanies the millennial turn in relation to environmental disaster and to the new forms of thinking it has catalyzed. She turns to 1990s Latin American vernacular culture, literary fiction, and social movements, which simultaneously registered neoliberalism’s devastating effects and pursued alternate ways of knowing and living. Tracing the workings of colonialism alongside the history of anticolonial struggles and Indigenous mobilizations in the Americas, Pratt analyzes indigeneity both as a key index of coloniality, neoliberal extraction, and ecological destruction, and as a source for alternative modes of thought and being. Ultimately, Pratt demonstrates that the changes on either side of the millennium have catalyzed new forms of world-making and knowledge-making in the face of an unknowable and catastrophic future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDecolonizationzLatin America. 0aPostcolonialismzLatin America. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022 Englishz978311099296008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022z9783110992939oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022909?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022909423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/i